        "username": "rassilon1963",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/rassilon1963/{size}/31625_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-07-22T10:43:32.010Z",
        "cooked": "<p>the functionality does not at the moment exist, and there is a feature request of the kind:</p><aside class=\"quote quote-modified\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"49643\">\n  <div class=\"title\">\n    <div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n    <img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/m/7c8e57/48.png\" class=\"avatar\">\n    <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/using-signal-without-internet-connection-inside-your-wan-or-lan/49643\">Using Signal without Internet connection (inside your WAN or LAN)</a> <a class=\"badge-category__wrapper \" href=\"/c/feature-requests/17\"><span data-category-id=\"17\" style=\"--category-badge-color: #83B72A; --category-badge-text-color: #FFFFFF;\" data-drop-close=\"true\" class=\"badge-category \" title=\"Post your ideas here for new features and functionality for the Signal app.\"><span class=\"badge-category__name\">Feature Requests</span></span></a>\n  </div>\n  <blockquote>\n    Yes there are apps like FireChat, Bridgefy, or Briar, that are using <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smartphone_ad_hoc_network\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">SPANs</a> But if your daily messaging app would be able to check the wireless network (it is connected to) for contacts/clients, when it realises that there is no internet connection, that would be fantastic! \nIf the Internet goes down, for whatever reason, people using signal would be prepared in that regard. They don’t have to be tech savvy to download and setting up the above mentioned apps… beforehand. My grandparents are using…\n  </blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>\ni’d venture a guess this is in no way a priority, both because of the large amount of refactoring that’ll be required to make it work, and because it’ll provide benefit to very few users, who can also download an existing no-internet app such as <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Briar_(software)\">Briar</a>.</p>",
